<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="chp4sec2" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Wilson's Theorem</title>

  <p> </p>
  
  <definition xml:id="definition-factorial">
    <title>Factorial</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            The <term>factorial of n</term>, denoted <m>n!</m>, is the product of all positive integers less than or equal to <m>n</m>.
        </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

<proposition xml:id="proposition-squares_roots_of_one_modulo_a_prime">
  <title>Squares of Roots of One Modulo a Prime</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>p</m> is a prime and <m>r</m> is an integer, then <m>r^2 \equiv 1 \pmod p</m> if and only if <m>r \equiv 1 \pmod p</m> or <m>r \equiv -1 \pmod p</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <proof>
    <p>
      Try a direct proof.  Begin with the forward direction.  Rewrite this as <m>r^2 - 1 \equiv 0 \pmod p</m>.  Factor the left and analyze.  The other direction is immediate.  You may find  <xref ref="proposition-congruence_preserves_operations"/>, <xref ref="definition-prime_number"/>, <xref ref="definition-congruence"/>, and <xref ref="proposition-euclid_lemma"/> useful.
    </p>
  </proof>
</proposition>

<sage>
<input>
for i in prime_range(1,100):
    print(i,factorial(i-1)%i - i)
</input>
<output>
</output>
</sage>

<proposition xml:id="proposition-wilsons_theorem">
  <title>Wilson's Theorem</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>p</m> is a prime, then <m>(p-1)! \equiv -1 \pmod{p}</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <proof>
    <p>
      Try a direct proof.  Check <m> p=2,3</m> by hand.  Now suppose <m> p \ge 5</m>.  The big idea is you will want to group the elements of the product <m>1 \cdot 2 \cdot \cdots \cdot (p-1)</m> in a useful way.  You may find it useful to observe that <m>(p-1)!=(p-1)\cdot (p-2)!</m> and compute <m>(p-2)!</m> first.  Every least residue modulo <m>p</m> has a unique multiplicative inverse modulo <m>p</m> (why???).  When are these distinct?  When they are distinct, pair an element with its inverse.  You may find  <xref ref="definition-commutative_ring"/>, <xref ref="proposition-relatively_prime_elements_are_units_modulo_n"/>, <xref ref="proposition-squares_roots_of_one_modulo_a_prime"/>, <xref ref="definition-units_modulo_n"/>, and <xref ref="definition-congruence"/> useful.
    </p>
  </proof>
</proposition>

<sage>
<input>
for i in range(2,50):
    if is_prime(i)==false:
        print(i,factorial(i-1)%i)
</input>
<output>
</output>
</sage>


<proposition xml:id="proposition-wilsons_converse_theorem">
  <title>Wilson's Converse Theorem</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>n</m> is a not prime, then <m>(n-1)! \not\equiv -1 \pmod{n}</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <proof>
    <p>
      Try a direct proof by cases.  First check <m>n=4</m>.  Next suppose <m>n=p^2</m> where <m>p</m> is a prime greater than 2.  Then <m>p</m> and <m>2p</m> are both distinct least residues modulo <m>n</m> (why???).  What are the implications? Lastly, suppose <m>n</m> is not the square of a prime.  Then there are distinct least residues <m>a</m> and  <m>b</m> modulo <m>n</m> such that <m>ab = n</m> (why???).  What are the implications?  You may find  <xref ref="definition-prime_number"/> and <xref ref="definition-congruence"/> useful.
    </p>
  </proof>
</proposition>


</section>